      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qbtrain-mistakes">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why training pays for itself</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">The habits that quietly turn into cleanup.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Almost every messy QuickBooks file traces back to a handful of teachable habits. Training prevents these at the source &mdash; which is far cheaper than paying to undo them later.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for m in mistakes %}
      <div class="stack-8">
        <h3>{{ m.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="prose">{{ m.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qbtrain-covers">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">What the training covers</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Six skill areas, taught on your own file.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">The training plan is scoped to where you and your team actually need it. The six areas below cover the skills that keep a QuickBooks file clean; the mix depends on who&rsquo;s being trained and which product you run.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for c in covers %}
      <div class="stack-8">
        <h3>{{ c.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="prose">{{ c.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qbtrain-products">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Online, Desktop, Enterprise</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Training is product-specific &mdash; because the products are different.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">QuickBooks Online and QuickBooks Desktop are not the same software with a different login &mdash; the navigation, the bank-feed model, and the available features differ enough that generic training leaves gaps. Training is taught against the product you actually run.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for p in products %}
      <div class="stack-8">
        <h3>{{ p.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="prose">{{ p.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qbtrain-how">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">How a training engagement works</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">From discovery call to confident team.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Training is scoped before it starts so the sessions target what you actually need &mdash; not a fixed curriculum read off a slide deck.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="stack-8">
      {%- for step in how %}
      <div class="stack-8">
        <p class="section__eyebrow">{{ step.num }}</p>
        <h3>{{ step.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="prose">{{ step.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qbtrain-pricing">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Pricing</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Scoped to what you need, quoted in writing.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Training is not a fixed package with a sticker price, because needs vary enormously &mdash; one person learning bank feeds is a different engagement from a five-person team learning the full monthly routine. We don&rsquo;t publish a per-hour or per-session rate we can&rsquo;t stand behind for your situation. Here is exactly how pricing works.</p>
    </header>
    <ul class="checks-list">
      {%- for li in pricing %}<li>{{ li | safe }}</li>{%- endfor %}
    </ul>
    <p class="section__lede">The discovery call is free and carries no obligation. You leave it with a written scope and quote; if training isn&rsquo;t the right fit, we&rsquo;ll point you to the engagement that is.</p>
  </div>
</section>

